Anga nyasa, kara nyasa etc are just formalities for most =
of us. Hardly any of us can actually "place" (root verb "nyas" means "to pl=
ace") syllables in body parts by visualizing, and then hearing, those sound=
s in specific locations within oneself.
Technically, nyasas etc before invo=
king a deity (or a mantra) create a conducive *environment* for an energy t=
o manifest within one, close the area off, so that one can focus and worshi=
p that energy. Though it's a formality anyway for most of us, I kept it in =
the manuals just in case - who knows, it may help someone.

If one is indee=
d able to create the right environment and close the area off, there is no =
need to redo it at the very end, like done in some rituals. So I see no rea=
l purpose behind doing nyasas at the very end. Digvimoka may have a purpose=
, but, the step of sending off the deity can handle that.

To put it in dif=
ferent words, I retained some steps conducive to manifesting an energy with=
in oneself (or fire), in case those steps may augment someone's experience.=
 Once the energy is manifested, I'd suggest leaving everything (including t=
he undoing of the environment) to that energy. Just contemplate/worship it,=
 and send it offin the end, respectfully/lovingly. That energy will do what=
ever needs to be done.


If you wish, you can redo nyasas and digvimoka (or=
 no nyasas, but just digvimoka - "OM bhUrbhuvassuvarom iti digvimokaH") at =
the end, before sending off deity.

The most important thing is intensely f=
eel the presence of deity, in a way that is not self-centered.


